i>maloré</i>, <i>maleuré</i> ‘ill-fortuned, unlucky’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mallery","meanings":["English: variant of   Mallory  ."]},{"name":"Mallary","meanings":["English: variant of   Mallory  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Mallory was born in 1191, in Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Mallory Lord Kirkby, was 24 and his mother, Isue Aliseu, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Margaret. He died in 1247, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1191–1247":"1191–1247","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1192–1222":"1192–1222","1217–1259":"1217–1259","1167–1199":"1167–1199","1169–1199":"1169–1199","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","1169":"1169","Aft 1199":"pärast 1199","1222":"1222","1167":"1167","1199":"1199","1198":"1198","1192":"1192","1191":"1191","Tachebrook Mallory, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, England":"Kirkby Mallory, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kirby